      \field{abstract}{Given a graph G = (S,E), the problem dealt with in this paper consists in partitioning S into a disjoint union of cliques by adding or removing a minimum number z(G) of edges. The problem, which is refered to by the Zahn Problem (ZP), is NP-hard in general.}
      \field{annotation}{Overview: Zahn's decision problem can be described as the problem of partitioning a graph G=(S,E) into a subset of disjoint cliques by either removing or adding the minimum amount of edges. This problem is known to be NP-hard in general. This paper provides a constraint programming approach to Zahn's decision problem, by converting the graph into a set of boolean variables and soft constraints . The WSCP is then solved using the toulbar2 solver. Review: This paper provides the first CSP approach to Zahn’s graph clustering problem. The results found in the paper are promising: the results found are competitive, especially on large problems. This shows that the soft arc consistency method used in toulbar2 can be applied to improve graph clustering. The model is also flexible, as new constraints can be added for different variations of the ZP.}
