      \field{abstract}{Designing decentralized policies for wireless communication networks is a crucial problem, which has only been partially solved in the literature so far. In this paper, we propose a Decentralized Markov Decision Process (Dec-MDP) framework to analyze a wireless sensor network with multiple users which access a common wireless channel. We consider devices with energy harvesting capabilities, that aim at balancing the energy arrivals with the data departures and with the probability of colliding with other nodes. Over time, an access point triggers a SYNC slot, wherein it recomputes the optimal transmission parameters of the whole network, and distributes this information. Every node receives its own policy, which specifies how it should access the channel in the future, and, thereafter, proceeds in a fully decentralized fashion, with no interactions with other entities in the network. We propose a multi-layer Markov model, where an external MDP manages the jumps between SYNC slots, and an internal Dec-MDP computes the optimal policy in the short term. We numerically show that, because of the harvesting, stationary policies are suboptimal in energy harvesting scenarios, and the optimal trade-off lies between an orthogonal and a random access system.}
      \field{annotation}{REVIEW : This paper addresses the challenge of designing optimal decentralized transmission policies for Wireless Sensor Networks (WSNs) utilizing Energy Harvesting (EH) devices. The authors propose a multi-layer Markov model to balance energy arrivals, data departures, and packet collisions: an external Markov Decision Process (MDP) manages synchronization (SYNC) slots where an Access Point distributes the policy, while an internal Decentralized-MDP (Dec-MDP) dictates the nodes' autonomous actions between SYNC slots. To bypass the computationally prohibitive exhaustive search required to solve the continuous-state occupancy-MDP, the authors reformulate the exhaustive backup operation as a Constraint Program. Specifically, the optimization step is cast as a Weighted Constraint Satisfaction Problem (WCSP). Crucially for this review, the authors utilized the TOULBAR2 solver to execute all numerical evaluations and efficiently solve these internal WCSPs. Through this framework, the study demonstrates that a well-designed decentralized policy achieves performance close to centralized schemes, and proves that hybrid access schemes outperform pure orthogonal (TDMA-like) access in energy-constrained scenarios. OVERVIEW : Lien entre l'IA (Stochastique) et les WCSP : L'article modélise le problème avec des Processus de Décision Markoviens (MDP). Les MDP sont le fondement mathématique de l'Apprentissage par Renforcement, une branche importante de l'IA. Contrairement aux problèmes classiques où l'on donne tout à TOULBAR2 d'un seul coup (comme pour les protéines), ici TOULBAR2 est utilisé comme un sous-programme. À chaque itération de l'algorithme d'IA (pour évaluer les états de Markov), on génère un WCSP qu'on fait résoudre à TOULBAR2 pour trouver la meilleure action. Cela prouve que les WCSP peuvent être intégrés dans des boucles d'apprentissage dynamiques. Réduction de la complexité : L'article souligne que la recherche exhaustive dans ces modèles décentralisés est de complexité exponentielle, et que formuler le problème sous forme de WCSP permet de calculer des qui seraient autrement impossibles à évaluer.}
